    <q:item id="analog" type="text-response">
	  <q:question>
	    <section id="secanalog">
	    <title>Analog Computers</title>
	    <para id="anap1">
	    So-called <term>analog computers</term> use circuits to solve mathematical problems, particularly when they involve differential equations.
	    Suppose we are given the following differential equation to solve.
	    <m:math display="block">
          <m:apply><m:eq/>
            <m:apply><m:plus/>
              <m:apply><m:diff/>
	            <m:bvar><m:ci>t</m:ci></m:bvar>
	            <m:apply><m:ci type="fn">y</m:ci><m:ci>t</m:ci></m:apply>
              </m:apply>
              <m:apply><m:times/>
                <m:ci>a</m:ci>
	            <m:apply><m:ci type="fn">y</m:ci><m:ci>t</m:ci></m:apply>
              </m:apply>
            </m:apply>
	        <m:apply><m:ci type="fn">x</m:ci><m:ci>t</m:ci></m:apply>
          </m:apply>
	    </m:math>
        In this equation,
        <m:math><m:ci>a</m:ci></m:math> is a constant.
        </para>
        
        <list id="list_analist" list-type="enumerated">
          <item>
          When the input is a unit step
          (<m:math>
            <m:apply><m:eq/>
              <m:apply><m:ci type="fn">x</m:ci><m:ci>t</m:ci></m:apply>
              <m:apply><m:ci type="fn">u</m:ci><m:ci>t</m:ci></m:apply>
            </m:apply>
          </m:math>), the output is given by
          <m:math>
            <m:apply><m:eq/>
              <m:apply><m:ci type="fn">y</m:ci><m:ci>t</m:ci></m:apply>
              <m:apply><m:times/>
                <m:apply><m:minus/>
                  <m:ci>1</m:ci>
                  <m:apply><m:exp/>
                    <m:apply><m:minus/>
                      <m:apply><m:times/>
                        <m:ci>a</m:ci><m:ci>t</m:ci>
                      </m:apply>
                    </m:apply>
                  </m:apply>
                </m:apply>
                <m:apply><m:ci type="fn">u</m:ci><m:ci>t</m:ci></m:apply>
              </m:apply>
            </m:apply>
          </m:math>.
What is the total energy expended by the input?
         </item>
         
         <item>
         Instead of a unit step, suppose the input is a unit pulse (unit-amplitude, unit-duration) delivered to the circuit at time
         <m:math>
           <m:apply><m:eq/>
             <m:ci>t</m:ci>
             <m:cn>10</m:cn>
           </m:apply>
         </m:math>.
What is the output voltage in this case?
Sketch the waveform.
         </item>
         
        </list>
	    </section>
	  </q:question>
	</q:item>


